    (17, 200000, true, '["https://cdn.tgdd.vn/Products/Images/54/227725/tai-nghe-chup-tai-bluetooth-sony-wh-1000xm4-bac-1-org.jpg","https://cdn.tgdd.vn/Products/Images/54/227725/tai-nghe-chup-tai-bluetooth-sony-wh-1000xm4-bac-3-org.jpg","https://cdn.tgdd.vn/Products/Images/54/227725/tai-nghe-chup-tai-bluetooth-sony-wh-1000xm4-bac-4-org.jpg"]', '<h5 class=\"mb-3 mt-3 p-3\" style=\"font-weight: bold; border-left: 5px solid #6963ff\">✏️ 10/01/2022 20:31:46</h5><p><span style=\"font-size:18px;\">The Sony WH-1000XM4 is finally here. Its predecessor, the Sony WH-1000XM3 headphones, stole the crown from Bose back when they were first released back in 2018—and we’ve been waiting for a successor since then. Now Sony has released the new and improved headset that adds multipoint connectivity at the expense of aptX. But is it enough to compete in a crowded field of active noise cancelling (ANC) headphones?</span></p><ul><li><i>Everyone.</i> I can’t think of anyone who wouldn’t enjoy owning these. If you have the cash to splurge on a top-tier pair of headphones these are a no-brainer.</li><li><i>People who want the best active noise cancelling.</i> The <a href=\"https://www.soundguys.com/sony-wh-1000xm3-wireless-bluetooth-headphones-review-19824/\">WH-1000XM3</a> was already a great pair of active noise cancelling (ANC) headphones, and now the WH-1000XM4 is even better.</li><li><i>Commuters and jet-setters&nbsp;</i>will appreciate the battery life, noise canceling, sound quality, and not needing to choose between them.</li></ul><h2>What’s it like to use the Sony WH-1000XM4?</h2><figure class=\"image\"><img src=\"https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-2-of-10-1024x576.jpg\" alt=\"Sony WH-1000XM4 headphones on a yellow couch\" srcset=\"https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-2-of-10-1024x576.jpg 1024w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-2-of-10-300x169.jpg 300w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-2-of-10-768x432.jpg 768w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-2-of-10-1536x864.jpg 1536w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-2-of-10-16x9.jpg 16w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-2-of-10-32x18.jpg 32w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-2-of-10-28x16.jpg 28w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-2-of-10-56x32.jpg 56w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-2-of-10-64x36.jpg 64w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-2-of-10-712x400.jpg 712w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-2-of-10-1000x563.jpg 1000w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-2-of-10-1200x675.jpg 1200w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-2-of-10-560x315.jpg 560w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-2-of-10-365x205.jpg 365w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-2-of-10-818x460.jpg 818w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-2-of-10-711x400.jpg 711w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-2-of-10-418x235.jpg 418w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-2-of-10.jpg 1920w\" sizes=\"100vw\" width=\"1024\"></figure><p style=\"text-align:center;\">The Sony WH-1000XM4 doesn’t look too different from the originals except for a few slight tweaks.</p><p>While the WH-1000XM4 headphones are almost identical in looks to their predecessor, there are some new features tucked away inside. <a href=\"https://www.soundguys.com/bluetooth-multipoint-explained-28601/\">Bluetooth multipoint</a> makes them just slightly more convenient in everyday use by letting you connect to two devices at once (more on that later). It makes it easy transitioning from listening to music while working at your desk to watching a YouTube video on your phone, and back again, all without opening your Bluetooth settings. This was one of the biggest complaints with the WH-1000XM3, and having it here in the Sony WH-1000XM4 is definitely going to make plenty of people happy, with one big caveat. If you’re going to use multipoint, both connected devices need to use the <a href=\"https://www.soundguys.com/the-ultimate-guide-to-bluetooth-headphones-aac-20296/\">AAC Bluetooth codec</a>.</p><figure class=\"image\"><img src=\"https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-3-of-10-1024x576.jpg\" alt=\"Sony WH-1000XM4 headphones next to iPad Pro on a marble surface\" srcset=\"https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-3-of-10-1024x576.jpg 1024w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-3-of-10-300x169.jpg 300w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-3-of-10-768x432.jpg 768w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-3-of-10-1536x864.jpg 1536w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-3-of-10-16x9.jpg 16w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-3-of-10-32x18.jpg 32w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-3-of-10-28x16.jpg 28w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-3-of-10-56x32.jpg 56w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-3-of-10-64x36.jpg 64w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-3-of-10-712x400.jpg 712w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-3-of-10-1000x563.jpg 1000w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-3-of-10-1200x675.jpg 1200w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-3-of-10-560x315.jpg 560w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-3-of-10-365x205.jpg 365w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-3-of-10-818x460.jpg 818w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-3-of-10-711x400.jpg 711w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-3-of-10-418x235.jpg 418w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-3-of-10.jpg 1920w\" sizes=\"100vw\" width=\"1024\"></figure><p style=\"text-align:center;\">The addition of Bluetooth multipoint means you can stay connected to two devices at once.</p><p>Aside from the ability to stay connected to two devices at once, there’s also a few new features you can only access if you download the <a href=\"https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=com.sony.songpal.mdr&amp;hl=en_US\">Sony Headphones Connect</a> app, such as the speak to chat functionality. When turned on this will pause your music whenever the headphones detect that you’re speaking. While it definitely works, the feature treads a fine line between useful and annoying, especially considering how sensitive the detection is.</p><p>For example, while listening to a podcast, the headphones paused the media when I chuckled at a joke. You’re never really aware of how many weird sounds you make until you’re wearing a pair of headphones that pause your music each and every time you make one. It could be useful to some people, but many will probably just turn it off.</p><figure class=\"image\"><img src=\"https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-8-of-10-1024x576.jpg\" alt=\"Close-up of the proximity sensor on the inside of the left earcup of the Sony WH-1000XM4 headphones.\" srcset=\"https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-8-of-10-1024x576.jpg 1024w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-8-of-10-300x169.jpg 300w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-8-of-10-768x432.jpg 768w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-8-of-10-1536x864.jpg 1536w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-8-of-10-16x9.jpg 16w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-8-of-10-32x18.jpg 32w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-8-of-10-28x16.jpg 28w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-8-of-10-56x32.jpg 56w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-8-of-10-64x36.jpg 64w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-8-of-10-712x400.jpg 712w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-8-of-10-1000x563.jpg 1000w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-8-of-10-1200x675.jpg 1200w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-8-of-10-560x315.jpg 560w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-8-of-10-365x205.jpg 365w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-8-of-10-818x460.jpg 818w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-8-of-10-711x400.jpg 711w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-8-of-10-418x235.jpg 418w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-8-of-10.jpg 1920w\" sizes=\"100vw\" width=\"1024\"></figure><p style=\"text-align:center;\">The headphones have a new sensor in the left earcup that will auto-pause your music when you take them off.</p><p>Along the same lines is the auto-pause feature, which stops playback when you remove the headphones. On the inside of the left earcup is a small sensor that detects when you’re wearing the headphones or not, and pauses music when you take the headphones off. Is it a must-have feature? Absolutely not, but it’s the kind of subtle touch that you’d expect from a $350 pair of headphones and Sony nailed it here.</p><p>The actual earcups are also slightly thicker than the previous pair, which results in <a href=\"https://www.soundguys.com/what-is-isolation-12506/\">better isolation</a> even when noise cancelling is turned off. On the other hand, the headband itself is thinner with a little less padding, and I have to say I felt the difference here. While these are definitely comfortable, there was an ever-present pressure at the crown of my head that only became more pronounced with longer listening sessions.</p><blockquote><p>When you place your hand over the left ear cup, ambient mode immediately activates.</p></blockquote><p>The headphones’ controls haven’t changed much. Both earcups are still touch-sensitive and you control playback with a series of taps and swipes. Unfortunately, the double-tap to pause function only actually works some of the time. Swiping to control volume and skip between songs works seamlessly, but for some reason, the headphones struggle to register taps. Sometimes it’s easier and quicker to simply take off the headphones and let them auto-pause—the pause functionality worked roughly 25% of the time for me.</p><p>Cupping your hand over the left earcup activates ambient mode, which is still one of my favorite features. It dramatically lowers the music and uses the microphones built into the headphones to play what’s going on around you. Not a huge deal for anyone still spending most of their time at home like I am, but useful if you need to quickly catch an announcement from the pilot or train conductor <a href=\"https://www.soundguys.com/best-bluetooth-headphones-for-commuting-29238/\">while commuting</a>.</p><h2>How well does the Sony WH-1000XM4 cancel noise?</h2><figure class=\"image\"><img src=\"https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/04/sony-wh-1000xm4-Isolation-HATS-1-1024x599.jpg\" alt=\"A chart showing that the active noise canceling performance of the Sony WH-1000XM4 is very good\" srcset=\"https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/04/sony-wh-1000xm4-Isolation-HATS-1-1024x599.jpg 1024w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/04/sony-wh-1000xm4-Isolation-HATS-1-300x175.jpg 300w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/04/sony-wh-1000xm4-Isolation-HATS-1-768x449.jpg 768w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/04/sony-wh-1000xm4-Isolation-HATS-1-1536x898.jpg 1536w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/04/sony-wh-1000xm4-Isolation-HATS-1-16x9.jpg 16w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/04/sony-wh-1000xm4-Isolation-HATS-1-32x19.jpg 32w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/04/sony-wh-1000xm4-Isolation-HATS-1-28x16.jpg 28w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/04/sony-wh-1000xm4-Isolation-HATS-1-56x33.jpg 56w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/04/sony-wh-1000xm4-Isolation-HATS-1-64x37.jpg 64w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/04/sony-wh-1000xm4-Isolation-HATS-1-1000x585.jpg 1000w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/04/sony-wh-1000xm4-Isolation-HATS-1-1200x702.jpg 1200w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/04/sony-wh-1000xm4-Isolation-HATS-1-560x328.jpg 560w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/04/sony-wh-1000xm4-Isolation-HATS-1-365x213.jpg 365w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/04/sony-wh-1000xm4-Isolation-HATS-1-786x460.jpg 786w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/04/sony-wh-1000xm4-Isolation-HATS-1-684x400.jpg 684w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/04/sony-wh-1000xm4-Isolation-HATS-1-402x235.jpg 402w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/04/sony-wh-1000xm4-Isolation-HATS-1.jpg 1920w\" sizes=\"100vw\" width=\"1024\"></figure><p style=\"text-align:center;\">Among the best in its class, the Sony WH-1000XM4 offers very good noise cancelation and isolation.</p><p>If you were hoping for an improvement in <a href=\"https://www.soundguys.com/how-noise-cancelling-headphones-work-12380/\">noise cancelling</a> with the WH-1000XM4, these are going to make you very happy. Somehow, the team at Sony made the ANC even better than before.</p><p>Plots like the one above give a rough idea of how much noise is cancelled across the audible spectrum of 20Hz-20kHZ (the limits of human hearing). Taller peaks in the chart above correspond to more noise being removed. The WH-1000XM3 isn’t a slouch where ANC is concerned, but the Sony WH-1000XM4 is better in its ability to attenuate lower-frequency sounds like the low hum of an air conditioner, or the constant rumble of a jet engine than most other headsets.</p><h2>How do you pair to the Sony WH-1000XM4?</h2><p>&nbsp;</p><figure class=\"image\"><img src=\"https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-9-of-10-1024x576.jpg\" alt=\"Shot of the earcups and the padding on the Sony WH-1000XM4 headphones on a white table. \" srcset=\"https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-9-of-10-1024x576.jpg 1024w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-9-of-10-300x169.jpg 300w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-9-of-10-768x432.jpg 768w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-9-of-10-1536x864.jpg 1536w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-9-of-10-16x9.jpg 16w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-9-of-10-32x18.jpg 32w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-9-of-10-28x16.jpg 28w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-9-of-10-56x32.jpg 56w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-9-of-10-64x36.jpg 64w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-9-of-10-712x400.jpg 712w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-9-of-10-1000x563.jpg 1000w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-9-of-10-1200x675.jpg 1200w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-9-of-10-560x315.jpg 560w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-9-of-10-365x205.jpg 365w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-9-of-10-818x460.jpg 818w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-9-of-10-711x400.jpg 711w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-9-of-10-418x235.jpg 418w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-9-of-10.jpg 1920w\" sizes=\"100vw\" width=\"1024\"></figure><p style=\"text-align:center;\">The earcups are slightly larger than the previous version and the padding is a little less plush, but still comfortable.</p><p>Pairing to the Sony WH-1000XM4 is as simple as tapping your phone to the back of the NFC logo on the left earcup and following the prompt that appears on your <a href=\"https://www.soundguys.com/best-smartphones-for-audio-16373/\">smartphone</a>. If your smartphone doesn’t have NFC, you’ll need to pair the old-fashioned way by going into Bluetooth settings.</p><ol><li>Power on the headphones by holding down the power button.</li><li>If you’re doing this for the first time, the headphones will automatically enter pairing mode.</li><li>Next, you have to navigate to the Bluetooth settings on your device. Search for WH-1000XM4 in the list.</li><li>Tap them to connect.</li></ol><p>To pair a second device, it’s a similar process—except the headphones won’t automatically enter pairing mode when you turn them on since they’re already paired to another device.</p><p>To pair to a second device:</p><ol><li>Power off your headphones.</li><li>Just like before, hold down the power button to power on the headphones, but this time don’t let you go until you hear the pairing chime (or you see the small LED light start rapidly flashing blue.)</li><li>Navigate to Bluetooth settings on your second device.</li><li>Click on the WH-1000XM4 to connect.</li></ol><h2>How’s the connection strength?</h2><figure class=\"image\"><img src=\"https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-4-of-10-1024x576.jpg\" alt=\"Man holding Sony WH-1000XM4 headphones in front of green plants\" srcset=\"https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-4-of-10-1024x576.jpg 1024w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-4-of-10-300x169.jpg 300w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-4-of-10-768x432.jpg 768w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-4-of-10-1536x864.jpg 1536w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-4-of-10-16x9.jpg 16w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-4-of-10-32x18.jpg 32w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-4-of-10-28x16.jpg 28w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-4-of-10-56x32.jpg 56w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-4-of-10-64x36.jpg 64w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-4-of-10-712x400.jpg 712w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-4-of-10-1000x563.jpg 1000w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-4-of-10-1200x675.jpg 1200w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-4-of-10-560x315.jpg 560w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-4-of-10-365x205.jpg 365w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-4-of-10-818x460.jpg 818w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-4-of-10-711x400.jpg 711w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-4-of-10-418x235.jpg 418w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-4-of-10.jpg 1920w\" sizes=\"100vw\" width=\"1024\"></figure><p style=\"text-align:center;\">The Sony WH-1000XM4 headphones opt for a slightly thinner headband.</p><p>The Sony WH-1000XM4 are rocking Bluetooth 5.0, have Bluetooth multipoint, and support SBC, AAC,&nbsp;and Sony’s own <a href=\"https://www.soundguys.com/ldac-ultimate-bluetooth-guide-20026/\">LDAC</a>, which has the highest streaming quality possible if you’re willing to deal with a somewhat less-stable connection. If you’re using something that isn’t compatible with any of these codecs then it will default down to SBC, which is the most basic codec shared by all Bluetooth audio devices. Devices that don’t have Bluetooth at all can always connect via the included 3.5mm audio cable too.</p><p>However, multipoint capability is only available if you’re using AAC, and not LDAC or SBC. Depending on what you’re looking to do it might be worth it, but it’s not for me, as I spend most of my time using at least two devices.</p><figure class=\"image\"><img src=\"https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-6-of-10-1024x576.jpg\" alt=\"Close-up of 3.5mm input on Sony WH-1000XM4 headphones\" srcset=\"https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-6-of-10-1024x576.jpg 1024w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-6-of-10-300x169.jpg 300w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-6-of-10-768x432.jpg 768w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-6-of-10-1536x864.jpg 1536w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-6-of-10-16x9.jpg 16w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-6-of-10-32x18.jpg 32w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-6-of-10-28x16.jpg 28w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-6-of-10-56x32.jpg 56w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-6-of-10-64x36.jpg 64w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-6-of-10-712x400.jpg 712w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-6-of-10-1000x563.jpg 1000w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-6-of-10-1200x675.jpg 1200w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-6-of-10-560x315.jpg 560w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-6-of-10-365x205.jpg 365w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-6-of-10-818x460.jpg 818w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-6-of-10-711x400.jpg 711w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-6-of-10-418x235.jpg 418w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-6-of-10.jpg 1920w\" sizes=\"100vw\" width=\"1024\"></figure><p style=\"text-align:center;\">The WH-1000XM4 has a ton of Bluetooth codec options but thankfully still has a place for a standard 3.5mm audio cable as well.</p><p>I live in a fairly average-sized two-bedroom apartment, and in my testing I didn’t have any issues with range. While the headphones connected to my laptop I was able to walk around my entire apartment with no skips. The same held true with my Pixel 3 smartphone which managed to remain connected regardless of which pocket the phone was in.</p><h2>Should you get the Sony Headphones Connect app?</h2><figure class=\"image\"><img src=\"https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-7-of-10-1024x576.jpg\" alt=\"Pictured is a man using a Pixel 3 with the Sony Headphones app open\" srcset=\"https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-7-of-10-1024x576.jpg 1024w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-7-of-10-300x169.jpg 300w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-7-of-10-768x432.jpg 768w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-7-of-10-1536x864.jpg 1536w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-7-of-10-16x9.jpg 16w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-7-of-10-32x18.jpg 32w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-7-of-10-28x16.jpg 28w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-7-of-10-56x32.jpg 56w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-7-of-10-64x36.jpg 64w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-7-of-10-712x400.jpg 712w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-7-of-10-1000x563.jpg 1000w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-7-of-10-1200x675.jpg 1200w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-7-of-10-560x315.jpg 560w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-7-of-10-365x205.jpg 365w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-7-of-10-818x460.jpg 818w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-7-of-10-711x400.jpg 711w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-7-of-10-418x235.jpg 418w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-7-of-10.jpg 1920w\" sizes=\"100vw\" width=\"1024\"></figure><p style=\"text-align:center;\">While the app isn’t the prettiest it does give you access to all the customization options you need and even some special features.</p><p>To get the most out of the WH-1000XM4 headphones, you will have to download the accompanying Sony Headphones Connect app that I mentioned earlier. While you’re able to rip the headphones out of the box and use them as is, you won’t be able to customize anything about them or use some of the cooler new features unless you use the app. For example, the second button on the headphones can be customized to either activate the assistant on your phone or toggle noise cancelling.</p><p>Unfortunately, you can’t have both—and downloading the app is the only way to choose whichever one you want. These are compatible with both the <a href=\"https://www.soundguys.com/best-headphones-google-assistant-20829/\">Google Assistant</a> and <a href=\"https://www.soundguys.com/best-alexa-speaker-23417/\">Amazon Alexa</a> so whichever one you prefer you can use these seamlessly.</p><blockquote><p>The headphones can be customized to either activate the assistant on your phone or toggle noise cancelling on/off, but not both.</p></blockquote><p>There are two other features unique to the app: noise cancelling optimization and 360-degree sound. While the noise cancelling is already excellent out of the box you can optimize it for whatever situation or level of air pressure you’re currently in via the app. You can also adjust the mix of ambient sound that’s fed through the headphones to your ear, so you can hear what’s going on around you. Of course, you can always cup your hand over the right earcup to allow a full passthrough so you can order a cardboard-tasting lunch from the friendly flight staff in economy class.</p><p>In the app there’s also a way to EQ the headphones to sound how you want them to. This isn’t exactly a new feature, but downloading the app is the only way to access it.</p><p>A slightly cooler feature that’s only available via the app, is access to Sony’s 360 Reality Audio. This is a new way of mastering music Sony has really been pushing and admittedly: it’s pretty awesome. You can only stream it on high-quality music services like <a href=\"https://www.soundguys.com/deezer-review-28852/\">Deezer</a>, <a href=\"https://www.soundguys.com/amazon-music-hd-review-29137/\">Amazon Music HD</a>, or <a href=\"https://www.soundguys.com/tidal-hifi-review-25846/\">Tidal</a>—if you’re already a subscriber, these are just that much more attractive, but if you’re on <a href=\"https://www.soundguys.com/why-choose-spotify-29103/\">Spotify</a> you’ll be missing out.</p><h2>How is the battery on the Sony WH-1000XM4?</h2><p>When it comes to battery life, Sony claims these will get you about 30 hours of constant playback which is the same as the previous WH-1000XM3. In our testing, we play music on a constant output of 75dB9SPL) with ANC on and we found that these last exactly 19 hours, 59 minutes (sorry Sony, we test down to the minute).</p><p>This is obviously still great and more than good enough for most people, but I find it odd this doesn’t last as long as its predecessor, which clocks in at about 24 hours. It’s entirely possible that as the unit we tested is a pre-production unit, there are some software gremlins yet to be solved, so we’ll re-test and update this review once the production unit comes in.</p><p>The Sony WH-1000XM4 charge via USB-C, and the quick charge feature will get you 5 hours of playtime after only 10 minutes of charging, which is fantastic if you’re already late to catch the bus or train.</p><h2>How does the Sony WH-1000XM4 sound?</h2><figure class=\"image\"><img src=\"https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/Sony-WH-1000XM4-frequency-response-HATS-soundguys-consumer-curve-v2-1024x672.jpg\" alt=\"A chart showing the frequency response of the Sony WH-1000XM4 compared to the SoundGuys\' house curve.\" srcset=\"https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/Sony-WH-1000XM4-frequency-response-HATS-soundguys-consumer-curve-v2-1024x672.jpg 1024w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/Sony-WH-1000XM4-frequency-response-HATS-soundguys-consumer-curve-v2-300x197.jpg 300w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/Sony-WH-1000XM4-frequency-response-HATS-soundguys-consumer-curve-v2-768x504.jpg 768w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/Sony-WH-1000XM4-frequency-response-HATS-soundguys-consumer-curve-v2-1536x1008.jpg 1536w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/Sony-WH-1000XM4-frequency-response-HATS-soundguys-consumer-curve-v2-16x11.jpg 16w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/Sony-WH-1000XM4-frequency-response-HATS-soundguys-consumer-curve-v2-32x21.jpg 32w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/Sony-WH-1000XM4-frequency-response-HATS-soundguys-consumer-curve-v2-28x18.jpg 28w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/Sony-WH-1000XM4-frequency-response-HATS-soundguys-consumer-curve-v2-56x37.jpg 56w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/Sony-WH-1000XM4-frequency-response-HATS-soundguys-consumer-curve-v2-64x42.jpg 64w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/Sony-WH-1000XM4-frequency-response-HATS-soundguys-consumer-curve-v2-184x120.jpg 184w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/Sony-WH-1000XM4-frequency-response-HATS-soundguys-consumer-curve-v2-1000x656.jpg 1000w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/Sony-WH-1000XM4-frequency-response-HATS-soundguys-consumer-curve-v2-1200x788.jpg 1200w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/Sony-WH-1000XM4-frequency-response-HATS-soundguys-consumer-curve-v2-560x368.jpg 560w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/Sony-WH-1000XM4-frequency-response-HATS-soundguys-consumer-curve-v2-365x240.jpg 365w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/Sony-WH-1000XM4-frequency-response-HATS-soundguys-consumer-curve-v2-701x460.jpg 701w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/Sony-WH-1000XM4-frequency-response-HATS-soundguys-consumer-curve-v2-609x400.jpg 609w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/Sony-WH-1000XM4-frequency-response-HATS-soundguys-consumer-curve-v2-358x235.jpg 358w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/Sony-WH-1000XM4-frequency-response-HATS-soundguys-consumer-curve-v2.jpg 1659w\" sizes=\"100vw\" width=\"1024\"></figure><p style=\"text-align:center;\">The Sony WH-1000XM4 (cyan) default frequency response amplifies bass and treble notes a bit more than our consumer curve (pink) suggests.</p><p>Sound quality for the Sony WH-1000XM4 is one of those subtle things Sony also improved over the last model. That’s not to say that the XM3 sounds <i>bad</i>—it sounds great—but the older model definitely has more of a consumer-friendly bump in the low end.</p><p>The more neutral-leaning <a href=\"https://www.soundguys.com/frequency-response-explained-16507/\">frequency response</a> in the lows translates to a sound that doesn’t get a huge bass boost as you’ll find on some other headphones. While it isn’t for everyone, most people (besides <a href=\"https://www.soundguys.com/best-headphones-for-bass-9605/\">bassheads</a>) won’t have a problem here. If you do want more low-end emphasis, you can always just change the <a href=\"https://www.soundguys.com/how-to-equalize-fine-tune-your-listening-experience-16410/\">EQ</a> preset in the app.</p><h3>Lows, mids, and highs</h3><p>As is, the bass is perfect for subtle performances like <a href=\"https://open.spotify.com/track/7IVkyo8IVhPsRuZwdfpoLo?si=h6fy2kCBR-u6BzVHEjUD0w\">Bach’s <i>Violin Partita No. 2 in D Minor</i></a> by Hilary Hahn, where the low notes hit at just the right volume. The rumbles at the beginning of <a href=\"https://open.spotify.com/track/66B8m2u4nLLZcbjAPu29w9?si=LQyCWe8YRY2A_TRbZ6fqMA\"><i>Pixel Empire</i></a> by Madeon also sound great, and you can hear the variations in the rumbles throughout the intro. That same attention to detail carries over to the mids.</p><p>The lyrics in <a href=\"https://open.spotify.com/track/5KVaCodaUwkM9vRoI0snIP?si=b8G-O-d0QHaEiV4kVJK15A\"><i>Constellations</i></a> by Darwin Deez are clearly audible throughout the entire song regardless of what’s going on. Cymbals, shakers, and claps throughout the song also benefit from the slight increase in volume. In short, these sound great.</p><h3>How to equalize the Sony WH-1000XM4 headphones</h3><p>If you want to make these headphones sound better than they already do, you can either use the equalizer in the Sony Headphones Connect app, or you can use a PC-based solution like Equalizer APO, Roon, or Voicemeeter. Follow the below chart as a loose guide for your adjustments to get the sound to better fit our house curve. From there, boost and cut targeted bands as you wish to get the desired result.</p><figure class=\"image\"><img src=\"https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/11/Sony-WH-1000XM4-EQ-suggestion-chart-HATS-SoundGuys-consumer-curve-V2-1024x672.jpeg\" alt=\"SoundGuys recommends boosting the 200Hz to 2kHz sliders up by about 5dB, while dropping the 5kHz to 9kHz sliders to -5dB.\" srcset=\"https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/11/Sony-WH-1000XM4-EQ-suggestion-chart-HATS-SoundGuys-consumer-curve-V2-1024x672.jpeg 1024w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/11/Sony-WH-1000XM4-EQ-suggestion-chart-HATS-SoundGuys-consumer-curve-V2-300x197.jpeg 300w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/11/Sony-WH-1000XM4-EQ-suggestion-chart-HATS-SoundGuys-consumer-curve-V2-768x504.jpeg 768w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/11/Sony-WH-1000XM4-EQ-suggestion-chart-HATS-SoundGuys-consumer-curve-V2-1536x1008.jpeg 1536w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/11/Sony-WH-1000XM4-EQ-suggestion-chart-HATS-SoundGuys-consumer-curve-V2-16x11.jpeg 16w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/11/Sony-WH-1000XM4-EQ-suggestion-chart-HATS-SoundGuys-consumer-curve-V2-32x21.jpeg 32w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/11/Sony-WH-1000XM4-EQ-suggestion-chart-HATS-SoundGuys-consumer-curve-V2-28x18.jpeg 28w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/11/Sony-WH-1000XM4-EQ-suggestion-chart-HATS-SoundGuys-consumer-curve-V2-56x37.jpeg 56w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/11/Sony-WH-1000XM4-EQ-suggestion-chart-HATS-SoundGuys-consumer-curve-V2-64x42.jpeg 64w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/11/Sony-WH-1000XM4-EQ-suggestion-chart-HATS-SoundGuys-consumer-curve-V2-184x120.jpeg 184w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/11/Sony-WH-1000XM4-EQ-suggestion-chart-HATS-SoundGuys-consumer-curve-V2-1000x656.jpeg 1000w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/11/Sony-WH-1000XM4-EQ-suggestion-chart-HATS-SoundGuys-consumer-curve-V2-1200x788.jpeg 1200w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/11/Sony-WH-1000XM4-EQ-suggestion-chart-HATS-SoundGuys-consumer-curve-V2-560x368.jpeg 560w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/11/Sony-WH-1000XM4-EQ-suggestion-chart-HATS-SoundGuys-consumer-curve-V2-365x240.jpeg 365w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/11/Sony-WH-1000XM4-EQ-suggestion-chart-HATS-SoundGuys-consumer-curve-V2-701x460.jpeg 701w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/11/Sony-WH-1000XM4-EQ-suggestion-chart-HATS-SoundGuys-consumer-curve-V2-609x400.jpeg 609w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/11/Sony-WH-1000XM4-EQ-suggestion-chart-HATS-SoundGuys-consumer-curve-V2-358x235.jpeg 358w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/11/Sony-WH-1000XM4-EQ-suggestion-chart-HATS-SoundGuys-consumer-curve-V2.jpeg 1659w\" sizes=\"100vw\" width=\"1024\"></figure><p style=\"text-align:center;\">Boosting mids and dropping highs a bit are enough to get the Sony WH-1000XM4 sounding its best.</p><p>We should mention that you should avoid getting too crazy with equalizers in general, as there is a point of diminishing returns. You may also not be able to get the granularity you’d need for an adjustment like this in apps with limited bands. Just take it slow and use a light hand, you’ll be fine.</p><h2>How is the microphone quality on the Sony WH-1000XM4?</h2><p>The microphone on the Sony WH-1000XM3 is good, and it isn’t much different here. There is a slight drop-off in the frequency response under around 150-200Hz which isn’t unusual for Bluetooth headphones, but it’s more pronounced than on the previous version. It’s likely an attempt to keep the <a href=\"https://www.soundguys.com/proximity-effect-explained-51333/\">proximity effect</a>—the pesky phenomenon that makes some podcasts and other recordings overly bassy—at bay. It should still be good enough to get you through your phone calls and Zoom meetings.</p><h2>Should you get the Sony WH-1000XM4?</h2><figure class=\"image\"><img src=\"https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-5-of-10-1024x576.jpg\" alt=\"Sony WH-1000XM4 headphones next to magazines on a wood bench\" srcset=\"https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-5-of-10-1024x576.jpg 1024w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-5-of-10-300x169.jpg 300w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-5-of-10-768x432.jpg 768w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-5-of-10-1536x864.jpg 1536w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-5-of-10-16x9.jpg 16w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-5-of-10-32x18.jpg 32w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-5-of-10-28x16.jpg 28w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-5-of-10-56x32.jpg 56w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-5-of-10-64x36.jpg 64w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-5-of-10-712x400.jpg 712w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-5-of-10-1000x563.jpg 1000w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-5-of-10-1200x675.jpg 1200w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-5-of-10-560x315.jpg 560w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-5-of-10-365x205.jpg 365w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-5-of-10-818x460.jpg 818w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-5-of-10-711x400.jpg 711w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-5-of-10-418x235.jpg 418w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Sony-WH-1000XM4-5-of-10.jpg 1920w\" sizes=\"100vw\" width=\"1024\"></figure><p style=\"text-align:center;\">The headphones have hinges so you can fold them to toss in your bag and the earcups can rotate 90 degrees.</p><p>If you’re in the market for the best pair of Bluetooth headphones you can get, then yes, the Sony WH-1000XM4 should be on your shortlist. As of November 1, 2021, you can purchase the Sony WH-1000XM4 for as low as $248 USD, making it a bargain buy. The previous WH-1000XM3 is still one of our most recommended headphones, and Sony made it even better. Bluetooth multipoint makes it way more convenient, and subtle improvements to the noise cancelling and sound quality make this a compelling buy.</p><p>If you have the Sony WH-1000XM3 already, there really isn’t a huge need to upgrade unless you absolutely <i>need</i> multipoint connectivity. However, if you’re looking to invest in your first big pair of noise cancelling headphones, almost everyone will love these.</p><h2>What about the Apple AirPods Max?</h2><figure class=\"image\"><img src=\"https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/12/Apple-AirPods-Max-04-scaled-1024x576.jpg\" alt=\"A man wears the Apple AirPods Max and adjusting volume via the digital crown.\" srcset=\"https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/12/Apple-AirPods-Max-04-scaled-1024x576.jpg 1024w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/12/Apple-AirPods-Max-04-scaled-300x169.jpg 300w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/12/Apple-AirPods-Max-04-scaled-768x432.jpg 768w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/12/Apple-AirPods-Max-04-scaled-1536x864.jpg 1536w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/12/Apple-AirPods-Max-04-scaled-2048x1152.jpg 2048w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/12/Apple-AirPods-Max-04-scaled-16x9.jpg 16w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/12/Apple-AirPods-Max-04-scaled-32x18.jpg 32w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/12/Apple-AirPods-Max-04-scaled-28x16.jpg 28w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/12/Apple-AirPods-Max-04-scaled-56x32.jpg 56w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/12/Apple-AirPods-Max-04-scaled-64x36.jpg 64w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/12/Apple-AirPods-Max-04-scaled-712x400.jpg 712w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/12/Apple-AirPods-Max-04-scaled-1000x563.jpg 1000w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/12/Apple-AirPods-Max-04-scaled-1200x675.jpg 1200w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/12/Apple-AirPods-Max-04-scaled-560x315.jpg 560w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/12/Apple-AirPods-Max-04-scaled-365x205.jpg 365w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/12/Apple-AirPods-Max-04-scaled-818x460.jpg 818w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/12/Apple-AirPods-Max-04-scaled-711x400.jpg 711w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/12/Apple-AirPods-Max-04-scaled-418x235.jpg 418w\" sizes=\"100vw\" width=\"1024\"></figure><p style=\"text-align:center;\">The Digital Crown is smooth and feels great for adjusting volume.</p><p><a href=\"https://www.soundguys.com/apple-airpods-max-first-impressions-44975/\">Apple’s AirPods Max</a> is the first pair of headphones from the company. They promise about 20 hours of constant playback with noise cancelling turned on, the same H1 chip that you’ll find in the <a href=\"https://www.soundguys.com/apple-airpods-pro-review-27106/\">AirPods Pro</a>, and a transparency mode as well. Unlike the WH-1000XM4, our <a href=\"https://www.soundguys.com/best-airpods-max-alternatives-50495/\">favorite AirPods Max alternative</a>, the AirPods Max doesn’t have touch-sensitive controls. Instead, all of the controls are in the digital crown at the top of the ear cup.</p><figure class=\"image\"><img src=\"https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/04/airpods-max-attenuation-HATS-1024x599.jpg\" alt=\"A chart showing the active noise cancellation performance of the Apple AirPods Max.\" srcset=\"https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/04/airpods-max-attenuation-HATS-1024x599.jpg 1024w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/04/airpods-max-attenuation-HATS-300x175.jpg 300w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/04/airpods-max-attenuation-HATS-768x449.jpg 768w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/04/airpods-max-attenuation-HATS-1536x898.jpg 1536w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/04/airpods-max-attenuation-HATS-16x9.jpg 16w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/04/airpods-max-attenuation-HATS-32x19.jpg 32w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/04/airpods-max-attenuation-HATS-28x16.jpg 28w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/04/airpods-max-attenuation-HATS-56x33.jpg 56w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/04/airpods-max-attenuation-HATS-64x37.jpg 64w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/04/airpods-max-attenuation-HATS-1000x585.jpg 1000w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/04/airpods-max-attenuation-HATS-1200x702.jpg 1200w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/04/airpods-max-attenuation-HATS-560x328.jpg 560w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/04/airpods-max-attenuation-HATS-365x213.jpg 365w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/04/airpods-max-attenuation-HATS-786x460.jpg 786w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/04/airpods-max-attenuation-HATS-684x400.jpg 684w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/04/airpods-max-attenuation-HATS-402x235.jpg 402w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/04/airpods-max-attenuation-HATS.jpg 1920w\" sizes=\"100vw\" width=\"1024\"></figure><p style=\"text-align:center;\">Apple’s first headset sounds great, mostly by virtue of the fact that it’s so good at eliminating noise.</p><p>Unfortunately, the AirPods Max runs you about $549 USD which is far from cheap. However, while the Sony WH-1000XM4 is much more affordable than Apple’s latest headphones, the AirPods Max does offer better ANC performance. The difference is noticeable, but both headsets do an exceptional job here—and if you were to ask us the increase in price isn’t worth the performance difference for most people, even if it is very good.</p><h2>What are some other options besides the WH-1000XM4?</h2><p>While the WH-1000XM4 are clearly great, there are <a href=\"https://www.soundguys.com/best-headphones-of-2020-2559/\">other options worth considering</a>. All of the following picks are more or less in the same price range, so if you’re looking to save a lot of money, check out our list for the best <a href=\"https://www.soundguys.com/noise-cancelling-headphones-100-7142/\">noise cancelling headphones under $100</a>—you won’t get all the bells and whistles, but there are still lots of great options.</p><p>They’re older, but the <a href=\"https://www.soundguys.com/sony-wh-1000xm3-wireless-bluetooth-headphones-review-19824/\">Sony WH-1000XM3</a> are hardly yesterday’s trash. These headphones sport top-notch noise cancelling, A+ battery, and mainly only trade the multipoint Bluetooth for the addition of aptX and aptX HD support. If lack of multipoint doesn’t matter to you, you might as well save yourself some cash and pick them up when they inevitably go on sale.</p><h3>Bose QuietComfort 45</h3><p>If you just want a pair of the best pure noise-cancelers around, the Bose QuietComfort 45 attenuate more outside noise than any other headphones out there—but they don’t sound quite as good. They’re more expensive and have fewer codecs, but their minimalist design looks really nice, though performance still lies with Sony.</p><figure class=\"image\"><img src=\"https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/bose-quietcomfort-45-frequency-response-vs-sony-wh-1000xm4-1024x672.jpg\" alt=\"A plot showing the less consistent frequency response of the Bose QuietComfort 45 compared to the popular Sony WH-1000XM4.\" srcset=\"https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/bose-quietcomfort-45-frequency-response-vs-sony-wh-1000xm4-1024x672.jpg 1024w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/bose-quietcomfort-45-frequency-response-vs-sony-wh-1000xm4-300x197.jpg 300w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/bose-quietcomfort-45-frequency-response-vs-sony-wh-1000xm4-768x504.jpg 768w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/bose-quietcomfort-45-frequency-response-vs-sony-wh-1000xm4-1536x1008.jpg 1536w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/bose-quietcomfort-45-frequency-response-vs-sony-wh-1000xm4-16x11.jpg 16w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/bose-quietcomfort-45-frequency-response-vs-sony-wh-1000xm4-32x21.jpg 32w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/bose-quietcomfort-45-frequency-response-vs-sony-wh-1000xm4-28x18.jpg 28w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/bose-quietcomfort-45-frequency-response-vs-sony-wh-1000xm4-56x37.jpg 56w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/bose-quietcomfort-45-frequency-response-vs-sony-wh-1000xm4-64x42.jpg 64w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/bose-quietcomfort-45-frequency-response-vs-sony-wh-1000xm4-184x120.jpg 184w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/bose-quietcomfort-45-frequency-response-vs-sony-wh-1000xm4-1000x656.jpg 1000w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/bose-quietcomfort-45-frequency-response-vs-sony-wh-1000xm4-1200x788.jpg 1200w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/bose-quietcomfort-45-frequency-response-vs-sony-wh-1000xm4-560x368.jpg 560w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/bose-quietcomfort-45-frequency-response-vs-sony-wh-1000xm4-365x240.jpg 365w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/bose-quietcomfort-45-frequency-response-vs-sony-wh-1000xm4-701x460.jpg 701w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/bose-quietcomfort-45-frequency-response-vs-sony-wh-1000xm4-609x400.jpg 609w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/bose-quietcomfort-45-frequency-response-vs-sony-wh-1000xm4-358x235.jpg 358w, https://www.soundguys.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/bose-quietcomfort-45-frequency-response-vs-sony-wh-1000xm4.jpg 1659w\" sizes=\"100vw\" width=\"1024\"></figure><p style=\"text-align:center;\">Compared to the popular Sony WH-1000XM4 (yellow), the Bose QuietComfort 45 offers a more accurate low end—but less consistent highs.</p><p>If you’re a bass lover, stick with the WH-1000XM4. However, not everyone likes that kind of sound—especially podcast junkies and classical music enthusiasts. Bose’s headphones are slick and offer a lot of good features—but if you want higher-bitrate codecs, stick with Sony.</p><h3>Share AONIC 50</h3><p>The <a href=\"https://www.soundguys.com/shure-aonic-50-review-30744/\">Shure AONIC 50</a> definitely doesn’t have as much hype as products from Bose and Sony, but it’s <i>awesome</i>. This rocks all the latest specs and Bluetooth codecs just like the WH-1000XM4, can use a USB-C cable as a wired connection, and it looks pretty great. The premium build quality, great sound, and impressive noise cancelling earn this an editor’s choice award. However, it’s debut price was more expensive at about $399 USD, so this is definitely the upgrade pick.</p><h3>Sennheiser PXC 550-II</h3><p>The Sennheiser <a href=\"https://www.soundguys.com/sennheiser-pxc-550-ii-review-37850/\">PXC 550-II</a> lacks a few of the top-tier features you’d expect of headphones (like USB-C charging), but for $199 USD, it’s an almost-unbeatable pick. You’ll get a sleek design, superb noise cancelling, Bluetooth multipoint, and great sound quality to boot. Definitely give this some consideration if you’re not sure how much money you want to spend.</p>', 9),
    (18, 200000, false, '["https://cdn01.dienmaycholon.vn/filewebdmclnew/DMCL21/Picture//Apro/Apro_product_27429/smart-tivi-crys_multi_0_670_1020.png.webp","https://cdn01.dienmaycholon.vn/filewebdmclnew/DMCL21/Picture//Apro/Apro_product_27429/smart-tivi-crys_multi_1_30_1020.png.webp","https://cdn01.dienmaycholon.vn/filewebdmclnew/DMCL21/Picture//Apro/Apro_product_27429/smart-tivi-crys_multi_2_94_1020.png.webp"]', '<h5 class=\"mb-3 mt-3 p-3\" style=\"font-weight: bold; border-left: 5px solid #6963ff\">✏️ 10/01/2022 20:39:03</h5><h2>Open up your smart 4K experience</h2><figure class=\"image\"><img src=\"https://images.samsung.com/is/image/samsung/p6pim/my/feature/others/my-feature-au7700-uhd-4k-smart-tv-2021-427588329?%24FB_TYPE_A_JPG%24\" alt=\"AU7700 displays intricately blended color graphics which demonstrate vivid crystal color.\"></figure><h2 style=\"text-align:center;\">Fine tuned colour for a vibrant, lifelike picture</h2><p style=\"text-align:center;\"><strong>PurColour</strong></p><p style=\"text-align:center;\">PurColour makes watching films feel almost like you\'re there. It enables the TV to express a huge range of colours for optimal picture performance, and an immersive viewing experience.&nbsp;</p><figure class=\"image\"><img src=\"https://images.samsung.com/is/image/samsung/p6pim/my/feature/others/my-feature-au7700-uhd-4k-smart-tv-2021-427588644?%24FB_TYPE_K_JPG%24\" alt=\"The painting on the right compared to the conventional on the left shows a wider range of colour production due to PurColour technology.\"></figure><h2 style=\"text-align:center;\">Feel lifelike shade of colour as intended in powerful 4K</h2><h3 style=\"text-align:center;\">Crystal Processor 4K</h3><p style=\"text-align:center;\">Powerful 4K upscaling ensures you get up to 4K resolution for the content you love. You\'ll also experience more lifelike colour expressions due to its sophisticated colour mapping technology.</p><figure class=\"image\"><img src=\"https://images.samsung.com/is/image/samsung/p6pim/my/feature/others/my-feature-au7700-uhd-4k-smart-tv-2021-427588771\" alt=\"The crystal processor chip is shown. The Samsung logo as well as the Crystal Processor 4K logo can be seen on top.\"></figure><h2 style=\"text-align:center;\">Smooth motion for a clear picture</h2><h3 style=\"text-align:center;\">Motion Xcelerator</h3><p style=\"text-align:center;\">Experience clear picture and performance because it automatically estimates and compensates frames for the source of contents.</p><figure class=\"image\"><img src=\"https://images.samsung.com/is/image/samsung/p6pim/my/feature/others/my-feature-au7700-uhd-4k-smart-tv-2021-427589025?%24FB_TYPE_A_JPG%24\" alt=\"A dirt bike racer looks clear and visible inside the UHD TV screen because of UHD TV motion xcelerator technology.\"></figure><h2 style=\"text-align:center;\">Feel the reality of 4K UHD Resolution</h2><h3 style=\"text-align:center;\">4K Resolution</h3><p style=\"text-align:center;\">4K UHD TV goes beyond regular FHD with 4x more pixels, offering your eyes the sharp and crisp images they deserve. Now you can see even the small details in the scene.</p><figure class=\"image\"><img src=\"https://images.samsung.com/is/image/samsung/p6pim/my/feature/others/my-feature-au7700-uhd-4k-smart-tv-2021-427589221?%24FB_TYPE_A_JPG%24\" alt=\"The flower image on the right compared to the left shows higher quality picture resolution created by 4K UHD technology.\"></figure><h2 style=\"text-align:center;\">See dark and light in every scene</h2><h3 style=\"text-align:center;\">HDR</h3><p style=\"text-align:center;\">High Dynamic Range increases the range of light levels on your TV so you can enjoy an enormous spectrum of colours and all the visual details, in even the darkest scenes.</p><p style=\"text-align:center;\">* Viewing experience may vary according to types of content and format.</p><figure class=\"image\"><img src=\"https://images.samsung.com/is/image/samsung/p6pim/my/feature/others/my-feature-au7700-uhd-4k-smart-tv-2021-427589245\" alt=\"See dark and light in every scene\"></figure><h2 style=\"text-align:center;\">TV and soundbar orchestrated in perfect harmony</h2><p style=\"text-align:center;\"><strong>Q-Symphony</strong></p><p style=\"text-align:center;\">Surround yourself with sound from TV and soundbar orchestrated in harmony. Q Symphony uniquely allows TV and soundbar speakers to operate simultaneously for better surround effect without muting TV speakers.&nbsp;</p><figure class=\"image\"><img src=\"https://images.samsung.com/is/image/samsung/p6pim/my/feature/others/my-feature-au7700-uhd-4k-smart-tv-2021-427589354?%24FB_TYPE_K_JPG%24\" alt=\"Simulated sound wave graphics from TV and soundbar demonstrate Q Symphony technology as they play sound together.\"></figure><h2 style=\"text-align:center;\">More screen, less bezel</h2><h3 style=\"text-align:center;\">3-Bezeless Design</h3><p style=\"text-align:center;\">A sleek and elegant design that draws you to the purest picture. Crafted with an effortless minimalistic style from every angle and a boundless design that sets new standards.</p><figure class=\"image\"><img src=\"https://images.samsung.com/is/image/samsung/p6pim/my/feature/others/my-feature-au7700-uhd-4k-smart-tv-2021-427589431?%24FB_TYPE_A_JPG%24\" alt=\"3-Bezeless Design of AU7000 can be seen on top of artistic angle of tunnel interior.\"></figure><h2 style=\"text-align:center;\">Eliminate clutter</h2><h3 style=\"text-align:center;\">Clean Cable Solution</h3><p style=\"text-align:center;\">Keep your cables tidy and conceal them, reducing clutter and keeping a seamless look for your TV.</p><p style=\"text-align:center;\">* Actual product may differ from image shown.</p><figure class=\"image\"><img src=\"https://images.samsung.com/is/image/samsung/p6pim/my/feature/others/my-feature-au7700-uhd-4k-smart-tv-2021-427589576\" alt=\"A close-up view of AU7000 on stand shows less viewing distraction from cables due to its Clean Cable Solution\"></figure><h2 style=\"text-align:center;\">Work and learn from home</h2><p style=\"text-align:center;\"><strong>PC on TV</strong></p><p style=\"text-align:center;\">Enjoy every possibility of what you can do. Easily access your PC, Laptop, and mobile seamlessly on your TV.</p><p style=\"text-align:center;\">* Remote connection to PC is only supported for Windows 10 Professional or later and Mac OS 10.5 or later. * Connecting smartphone with Samsung Dex requires a compatible mobile device. * Availability of services is subject to change without prior notice. * Internet connection on TV and PC is required.&nbsp;</p><figure class=\"image\"><img src=\"https://images.samsung.com/is/image/samsung/p6pim/my/feature/others/my-feature-au7700-uhd-4k-smart-tv-2021-427622248?%24FB_TYPE_K_JPG%24\" alt=\"In a living room home office, A TV screen shows PC on TV feature which allows home TV to connect to office PC.\"></figure><h2 style=\"text-align:center;\">Simply tap to connect</h2><h3 style=\"text-align:center;\">Tap View</h3><p style=\"text-align:center;\">Mirroring movies or music from your mobile to TV is as simple as a tap.When you tap your TV with your mobile, the TV senses the tap and mirrors automatically. So it\'s quick and easy to switch to the TV and continue enjoying your favorite content.</p><p style=\"text-align:center;\">* Tap View is available on Samsung Galaxy devices with Android OS 8.1 and higher.</p><figure class=\"image\"><img src=\"https://images.samsung.com/is/image/samsung/p6pim/my/feature/others/my-feature-au7700-uhd-4k-smart-tv-2021-427627040?%24FB_TYPE_G3_JPG%24\" alt=\"The top of the TV is shown.\"></figure><h2>&nbsp;</h2><figure class=\"table\"><table><tbody><tr><td><strong>General Feature</strong></td><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>BRAND</td><td>Samsung</td></tr><tr><td rowspan=\"9\">MODEL NAME</td><td>UA50AU7700</td></tr><tr><td>Remote Controller: Yes</td></tr><tr><td>Batteries (for Remote Control): Yes</td></tr><tr><td>Optical Stand Support(Y20 Studio1): Yes</td></tr><tr><td>Mini Wall Mount Support: Yes</td></tr><tr><td>Vesa Wall Mount Support: Yes</td></tr><tr><td>User Manual: Yes</td></tr><tr><td>E-Manual: Yes</td></tr><tr><td>Power Cable: Yes</td></tr><tr><td>COLOR</td><td>Black</td></tr><tr><td>LAUNCH YEAR</td><td>2021</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Display</strong></td><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>DISPLAY SIZE</td><td>50 (125 Cm)</td></tr><tr><td>SCREEN TYPE</td><td>LED</td></tr><tr><td>HD TECHNOLOGY &amp; RESOLUTION</td><td>3840 x 2160 Pixels</td></tr><tr><td>SMART TV</td><td>Yes</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Video Features</strong></td><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>BRIGHTNESS</td><td>Brightness Detection</td></tr><tr><td>PICTURE ENGINE</td><td>Crystal Processor 4K</td></tr><tr><td>PQI (PICTURE QUALITY INDEX)</td><td>2000</td></tr><tr><td rowspan=\"9\">OTHER VIDEO FEATURES</td><td>One Billion Color: Yes</td></tr><tr><td>HDR (High Dynamic Range): HDR</td></tr><tr><td>HDR 10+: Support</td></tr><tr><td>HLG (Hybrid Log Gamma): Yes</td></tr><tr><td>Contrast: Mega Contrast</td></tr><tr><td>Color: Pur Color</td></tr><tr><td>Contrast Enhancer: Yes</td></tr><tr><td>Auto Motion Plus: Yes</td></tr><tr><td>Film Mode: Yes</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Audio Features</strong></td><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>SPEAKER TYPE</td><td>2CH</td></tr><tr><td>SOUND TECHNOLOGY</td><td>Dolby Digital Plus</td></tr><tr><td>SPEAKER POWER OUTPUT (RMS)</td><td>20W</td></tr><tr><td>OTHER FEATURES</td><td>Q-Symphony: Q-Symphony</td></tr><tr><td>OTHER FEATURES</td><td>Blutooth Audio: Yes</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Smart Tv Features</strong></td><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>OPERATING SYSTEM</td><td>Tizen™</td></tr><tr><td>MULTI VOICE ASSISTANTS</td><td>Yes</td></tr><tr><td rowspan=\"5\">OTHERS SMART FEATURES</td><td>Bixby: US English, UK English, India English, Korean, French, German, Italian, Spanish, Portuguese (features vary by language)</td></tr><tr><td>Works with Google Assistant: Yes (India Only)</td></tr><tr><td>Works With Alexa: Yes (India Only)</td></tr><tr><td>SmartThings App Support: Yes</td></tr><tr><td>Univer</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Power</strong></td><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>VOLTAGE REQUIREMENT</td><td>AC220-240V 50/60Hz</td></tr><tr><td>POWER CONSUMPTION (MAX)</td><td>140 W</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Connectivity</strong></td><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>USB</td><td>1</td></tr><tr><td>HDMI</td><td>3</td></tr><tr><td>BUILT IN WI-FI</td><td>Yes</td></tr><tr><td>BLUETOOTH</td><td>Yes (BT5.2)</td></tr><tr><td rowspan=\"5\">OTHER FEATURES</td><td>Digital Audio Out (Optical): 1</td></tr><tr><td>RF In (Terrestrial / Cable input): 1/1(Common Use for Terrestrial)/0</td></tr><tr><td>HDMI A / Return Ch. Support: Yes</td></tr><tr><td>eARC: Yes</td></tr><tr><td>HDMI Quick Switch: Yes</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>', 5),
    (19, 50000, false, '["https://cdn01.dienmaycholon.vn/filewebdmclnew/DMCL21/Picture//Apro/Apro_product_27354/smart-nanocell-_multi_1_695_1020.png.webp","https://cdn01.dienmaycholon.vn/filewebdmclnew/DMCL21/Picture//Apro/Apro_product_27354/smart-nanocell-_multi_2_196_1020.png.webp","https://cdn01.dienmaycholon.vn/filewebdmclnew/DMCL21/Picture//Apro/Apro_product_27354/smart-nanocell-_multi_3_408_1020.png.webp"]', '<h5 class=\"mb-3 mt-3 p-3\" style=\"font-weight: bold; border-left: 5px solid #6963ff\">✏️ 10/01/2022 20:45:42</h5><p>For the last several years, LG\'s OLED TVs have become synonymous with high-end picture performance, repeatedly earning a top spot on numerous \"Best <a href=\"https://www.businessinsider.com/what-is-4k\">4K</a> TV\" lists.&nbsp;</p><p>But, while the company\'s OLED models have been celebrated, LG\'s LCD TVs, often branded as NanoCell, haven\'t received as much attention. Though decent performers, the NanoCells just haven\'t been able to equal the wow factor of LG\'s OLEDs or the value of LCD models from other manufacturers.</p><p>For its <a href=\"https://www.businessinsider.com/reviews/out?platform=browser&amp;postSource=bi%7C61b8efc8f2a36b1ac9f42fb4&amp;sc=false&amp;sessionid=1641822206189ftfv851z&amp;type=ALREADY-AFFILIATE-LINK-NOT-AMAZON&amp;u=https%3A%2F%2Fbestbuy.7tiv.net%2Fc%2F196318%2F614286%2F10014%3Fu%3Dhttps%253A%252F%252Fwww.bestbuy.com%252Fsite%252Flg-65-class-nanocell-90-series-led-4k-uhd-smart-webos-tv%252F6401917.p%253FskuId%253D6401917%26subId3%3Dxid%3Afr1641822212082dgi&amp;xid=fr1641822212082dgi\">2020 NanoCell 90 Series 4K TV</a>, however, LG has actually made some solid improvements over previous models, resulting in a display that stacks up a bit better against the competition. <a href=\"https://www.businessinsider.com/what-is-hdr-tv\">High dynamic range</a> (HDR) performance still lags behind a few cheaper models from other brands, but the TV\'s viewing angles and smart capabilities are among the best you can find for $1,199.99.</p><h2><strong>Design</strong></h2><p>LG\'s <a href=\"https://www.businessinsider.com/reviews/out?platform=browser&amp;postSource=bi%7C61b8efc8f2a36b1ac9f42fb4&amp;sc=false&amp;sessionid=1641822206189k676k2u0&amp;type=ALREADY-AFFILIATE-LINK-NOT-AMAZON&amp;u=https%3A%2F%2Fbestbuy.7tiv.net%2Fc%2F196318%2F614286%2F10014%3Fu%3Dhttps%253A%252F%252Fwww.bestbuy.com%252Fsite%252Flg-65-class-nanocell-90-series-led-4k-uhd-smart-webos-tv%252F6401917.p%253FskuId%253D6401917%26subId3%3Dxid%3Afr1641822212082bia&amp;xid=fr1641822212082bia\">65-inch NanoCell 90 4K TV</a> features an attractive but pretty standard design. It\'s unlikely to win over buyers based on style alone, yet it should look just fine situated on any home entertainment console or mounted on a wall.&nbsp;</p><p>The panel\'s profile measures about 2.8 inches thick, which is about average for an LCD TV that doesn\'t use edge-lit dimming. Unlike a lot of other TV models that feature thinner profiles at the top and then get thicker toward the bottom where the inputs are housed, the NanoCell 90 remains the same general thickness from top to bottom.&nbsp;</p><p>Left and right feet stands are included which need to be screwed into the bottom of the screen after unboxing. A thin bezel runs around the top and sides of the panel, while a thicker border rests at the bottom.&nbsp;</p><p>Inputs are housed on the back left of the screen, including four side-facing HDMI (one eARC) ports. Two of these HDMI connections feature support for the HDMI 2.1 specification, enabling new features, like Variable Refresh Rate (VRR), from compatible sources.</p><p>LG\'s unique Magic Remote is included with built-in <a href=\"https://www.businessinsider.com/what-is-google-assistant-how-to-use-customize\">Google Assistant</a> or Amazon Alexa voice control. The remote\'s somewhat large and thick design won\'t appeal to all buyers, but it does feature a cool point navigation option that allows you to move the cursor by pointing the remote at the screen. Anyone who\'s ever played a Nintendo Wii will be familiar with the process. You can also use the remote\'s scroll wheel and click buttons to navigate if you prefer.</p><h2><strong>Specs</strong></h2><ul><li>65-inch IPS LCD panel</li><li>4K Ultra HD 3,840 x 2,160 resolution</li><li>120Hz native refresh rate</li><li>Full-array local dimming</li><li>Dolby Vision, HDR10, and HLG support</li><li>NanoCell technology with wide color gamut capabilities</li><li>Measures 57.3 x 35.5 x 10.7 with feet stand attached</li><li>Weighs 54 pounds with feet stand attached</li><li>Four HDCP 2.2 compliant HDMI inputs (one eARC, two HDMI 2.1)</li><li>LG webOS platform</li><li>Wi-Fi, Apple AirPlay 2, and Ethernet connectivity</li><li>2-channel 20W down-firing speakers</li><li>Magic Remote with Google Assistant and Alexa</li></ul><h2 style=\"text-align:center;\"><strong>Setup</strong></h2><figure class=\"image image_resized\" style=\"width:646.391px;\"><img src=\"https://i.insider.com/5f6e604574fe5b0018a8d9fa?width=1300&amp;format=jpeg&amp;auto=webp\" alt=\"LG NanoCell 90 4K TV on wall\"></figure><p>After unpacking the TV, you simply need to attach the feet stands, hook up your external sources, and power on the display. The setup process is simple and requires going through the usual assortment of housekeeping items, like Wi-Fi configuration, firmware updates, and various privacy and terms of service agreements.</p><p>During setup, I hooked up an Onkyo AV receiver to the TV\'s HDMI Audio Return Channel (ARC). A <a href=\"https://www.businessinsider.com/best-4k-blu-ray-player#the-best-high-end-4k-blu-ray-player-3\">Panasonic 4K Ultra HD Blu-ray player</a>, a <a href=\"https://www.businessinsider.com/best-nintendo-switch-deals\">Nintendo Switch</a>, an <a href=\"https://www.businessinsider.com/best-xbox-deals\">Xbox One X</a>, and a <a href=\"https://www.businessinsider.com/best-streaming-box-stick#the-best-streaming-box-overall-1\">Roku Ultra</a> were all connected to the receiver and passed through to the display. In addition, a <a href=\"https://www.businessinsider.com/best-streaming-box-stick#the-best-amazon-fire-tv-5\">Fire TV Stick 4K</a> was hooked up directly to one of the TV\'s HDMI ports. After getting everything plugged in, all of my components passed through to the TV with no issues, enabling full 4K HDR and <a href=\"https://www.businessinsider.com/what-is-dolby-atmos\">Dolby Atmos</a> support when available.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>For those who\'d like to adjust the picture further, the NanoCell 90 offers plenty of presets and options, including a handy Filmmaker Mode setting. Endorsed by the Director\'s Guild of America (DGA), the Filmmaker Mode preset automatically deactivates unnecessary picture adjustments and processing, like motion smoothing and artificial sharpening, offering viewers a simple way to watch movies and shows closer to how the directors originally intended.&nbsp;</p><p>With that in mind, I recommend using Filmmaker Mode to get the most accurate Standard Dynamic Range (SDR) and High Dynamic Range (HDR) out-of-box picture. I also recommend using the High local dimming setting to get the best contrast. That being said, Filmmaker Mode is not available when watching Dolby Vision videos on <a href=\"https://www.businessinsider.com/what-is-streaming\">streaming</a> services or Ultra HD Blu-ray. For the most accurate Dolby Vision image, I recommend using the Cinema setting with local dimming set to High.&nbsp;</p><h2 style=\"text-align:center;\"><strong>Picture performance</strong></h2><figure class=\"image image_resized\" style=\"width:646.391px;\"><img src=\"https://i.insider.com/5f6e5ebb74fe5b0018a8d9f4?width=1300&amp;format=jpeg&amp;auto=webp\" alt=\"LG NanoCell 90 4K TV colors\"></figure><p><a href=\"https://www.businessinsider.com/reviews/out?platform=browser&amp;postSource=bi%7C61b8efc8f2a36b1ac9f42fb4&amp;sc=false&amp;sessionid=1641822206190iiz7byd1&amp;type=ALREADY-AFFILIATE-LINK-NOT-AMAZON&amp;u=https%3A%2F%2Fbestbuy.7tiv.net%2Fc%2F196318%2F614286%2F10014%3Fu%3Dhttps%253A%252F%252Fwww.bestbuy.com%252Fsite%252Flg-65-class-nanocell-90-series-led-4k-uhd-smart-webos-tv%252F6401917.p%253FskuId%253D6401917%26subId3%3Dxid%3Afr1641822212082dif&amp;xid=fr1641822212082dif\">LG\'s NanoCell 90</a> is a solid performer overall, but the display has some key strengths and weaknesses compared to other competing flagship and midrange LCD TVs on the market.&nbsp;</p><h3><strong>IPS viewing angles</strong></h3><p>Unlike a lot of LCD TVs from the competition, the NanoCell 90 uses an In-Plane Switching (IPS) panel instead of a Vertical Alignment (VA) panel. So, what\'s the difference between the two? Long story short, IPS panels are known for superior viewing angles, allowing images to look good even if you\'re sitting off to the side, while VA panels are known for better contrast and black levels.</p><p>In practice, the IPS screen\'s viewing angles don\'t disappoint. Off-axis colors and contrast tend to fade and distort a lot on LCD TVs from other brands, but the LG NanoCell 90 maintains its picture performance very well, even if you\'re sitting off to the side. This is great if your couch can\'t be set up directly in front of the TV or if you tend to have viewing parties with guests seated all around the room. Local dimming does become more noticeable when off-center but, in general, viewing angles are a key benefit of this model.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>General screen uniformity is also strong. Some faint irregularities are visible across the panel from time to time, but distracting vertical lines and instances of dirty screen effect are less intrusive than I\'ve seen on some TVs from Vizio and Hisense.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><h3><strong>Local dimming</strong></h3><p>Despite the IPS screen, contrast is surprisingly decent. This is in part because the NanoCell 90 includes full-array local dimming. Local dimming is a beneficial feature found on several midrange and high-end LCD TVs, allowing the screen to dim and brighten in specific sections.&nbsp;</p><p>That being said, the NanoCell 90 doesn\'t use as many dimming zones as most TVs in this price range. Though LG doesn\'t disclose an official number, the display features approximately 32 zones. For comparison\'s sake, <a href=\"https://www.businessinsider.com/reviews/out?platform=browser&amp;postSource=bi%7C61b8efc8f2a36b1ac9f42fb4&amp;sc=false&amp;sessionid=1641822206190xq33ajkx&amp;type=ALREADY-AFFILIATE-LINK-NOT-AMAZON&amp;u=https%3A%2F%2Fbestbuy.7tiv.net%2Fc%2F196318%2F614286%2F10014%3Fu%3Dhttps%253A%252F%252Fwww.bestbuy.com%252Fsite%252Fhisense-65-class-h9g-quantum-series-led-4k-uhd-smart-android-tv%252F6404014.p%253FskuId%253D6404014%26subId3%3Dxid%3Afr1641822212082hcc&amp;xid=fr1641822212082hcc\">Hisense\'s 65-inch H9G</a> ($999) features 132 zones, <a href=\"https://www.businessinsider.com/reviews/out?platform=browser&amp;postSource=bi%7C61b8efc8f2a36b1ac9f42fb4&amp;sc=false&amp;sessionid=1641822206190k73ik84x&amp;type=ALREADY-AFFILIATE-LINK-NOT-AMAZON&amp;u=https%3A%2F%2Fbestbuy.7tiv.net%2Fc%2F196318%2F614286%2F10014%3Fu%3Dhttps%253A%252F%252Fwww.bestbuy.com%252Fsite%252Ftcl-65-class-6-series-led-4k-uhd-smart-roku-tv%252F6424216.p%253FskuId%253D6424216%26subId3%3Dxid%3Afr1641822212082age&amp;xid=fr1641822212082age\">TCL\'s 6-Series</a> ($899) has 160 zones, and <a href=\"https://www.businessinsider.com/reviews/out?platform=browser&amp;postSource=bi%7C61b8efc8f2a36b1ac9f42fb4&amp;sc=false&amp;sessionid=1641822206190ftml01qg&amp;type=ALREADY-AFFILIATE-LINK-NOT-AMAZON&amp;u=https%3A%2F%2Fbestbuy.7tiv.net%2Fc%2F196318%2F614286%2F10014%3Fu%3Dhttps%253A%252F%252Fwww.bestbuy.com%252Fsite%252F65-class-p-series-quantum-series-led-4k-uhd-smart-vizio-smartcast-tv%252F6416449.p%253FskuId%253D6416449%26subId3%3Dxid%3Afr1641822212082hjd&amp;xid=fr1641822212082hjd\">Vizio\'s P-Series Quantum</a> ($1,199) features 200 zones. There are other factors that contribute to local dimming performance but, overall, the more zones the better.&nbsp;</p><p>The NanoCell 90 uses its relatively limited number of zones to achieve decent black level and brightness performance. In fact, standard dynamic range (SDR) content essentially looks flawless with no major dimming artifacts. This is pretty much par for the course when it comes to flagship 4K sets, however, and the real test comes down to how good <a href=\"https://www.businessinsider.com/what-is-hdr-tv\">high dynamic range</a> (HDR) content looks.&nbsp;</p><h3 style=\"text-align:center;\"><strong>HDR playback</strong></h3><figure class=\"image image_resized\" style=\"width:646.391px;\"><img src=\"https://i.insider.com/5f6e5e0d74fe5b0018a8d9ea?width=1300&amp;format=jpeg&amp;auto=webp\" alt=\"LG NanoCell 90 4K HDR gaming\"></figure><p>For testing purposes, I watched several 4K Ultra HD Blu-ray discs and HDR streaming titles from services like <a href=\"https://www.businessinsider.com/how-to-watch-netflix-free-shows-movies\">Netflix</a> and <a href=\"https://www.businessinsider.com/disney-plus\">Disney Plus</a>. Overall, HDR movies and shows look good, making strong use of the TV\'s wide color gamut and dimming.</p><p>Unlike a lot of other flagship LCDs that use quantum dots for expanded color, the <a href=\"https://www.businessinsider.com/reviews/out?platform=browser&amp;postSource=bi%7C61b8efc8f2a36b1ac9f42fb4&amp;sc=false&amp;sessionid=16418222061905z8xkr7z&amp;type=ALREADY-AFFILIATE-LINK-NOT-AMAZON&amp;u=https%3A%2F%2Fbestbuy.7tiv.net%2Fc%2F196318%2F614286%2F10014%3Fu%3Dhttps%253A%252F%252Fwww.bestbuy.com%252Fsite%252Flg-65-class-nanocell-90-series-led-4k-uhd-smart-webos-tv%252F6401917.p%253FskuId%253D6401917%26subId3%3Dxid%3Afr1641822212082fii&amp;xid=fr1641822212082fii\">NanoCell 90</a> actually utilizes a slightly different process that integrates a nanoparticle filter on the panel. The end result provides a similar range of colors. When judging the TV\'s HDR performance as a whole, however, there are some issues worth pointing out.&nbsp;</p><p>First and foremost, the NanoCell 90 can\'t get as bright as some other 4K HDR TVs in the $800 to $1,200 range. Peak brightness hovers around the 500 nit mark, which is quite a bit under the 1,000 nit benchmark that a lot of HDR videos are graded for. The similarly-priced <a href=\"https://www.businessinsider.com/reviews/out?platform=browser&amp;postSource=bi%7C61b8efc8f2a36b1ac9f42fb4&amp;sc=false&amp;sessionid=1641822206190r9cf6qpc&amp;type=ALREADY-AFFILIATE-LINK-NOT-AMAZON&amp;u=https%3A%2F%2Fbestbuy.7tiv.net%2Fc%2F196318%2F614286%2F10014%3Fu%3Dhttps%253A%252F%252Fwww.bestbuy.com%252Fsite%252F65-class-p-series-quantum-series-led-4k-uhd-smart-vizio-smartcast-tv%252F6416449.p%253FskuId%253D6416449%26subId3%3Dxid%3Afr1641822212082ajf&amp;xid=fr1641822212082ajf\">Vizio P-Series Quantum</a> and the less-expensive <a href=\"https://www.businessinsider.com/reviews/out?platform=browser&amp;postSource=bi%7C61b8efc8f2a36b1ac9f42fb4&amp;sc=false&amp;sessionid=1641822206190ik7sgt06&amp;type=ALREADY-AFFILIATE-LINK-NOT-AMAZON&amp;u=https%3A%2F%2Fbestbuy.7tiv.net%2Fc%2F196318%2F614286%2F10014%3Fu%3Dhttps%253A%252F%252Fwww.bestbuy.com%252Fsite%252Fhisense-65-class-h9g-quantum-series-led-4k-uhd-smart-android-tv%252F6404014.p%253FskuId%253D6404014%26subId3%3Dxid%3Afr1641822212082cae&amp;xid=fr1641822212082cae\">Hisense H9G</a> are both capable of exceeding 1,000 nits.&nbsp;</p><p>What does this actually mean when watching HDR content on the TV? Basically, the bright highlights don\'t pop quite as much as they do on some competing models in this class. If this TV was placed side by side with one of the Vizio or Hisense models mentioned above, the brightest highlights in HDR videos would likely appear less intense and dimensional on the NanoCell 90.&nbsp;</p><p>It is a bit disappointing to see such average peak brightness numbers on a 65-inch LCD in this price range, but the TV\'s image quality does still benefit from its support for HDR. In fact, judged on its own, I rarely feel like I was missing all that much when watching HDR10 videos on the TV.</p><p>Black levels are also solid but the NanoCell 90 rarely provides the inky quality that better LCDs are capable of. Bars above and below the picture in widescreen movies, for instance, tend to remain a dark gray rather than true black.</p><p>Dimming artifacts, like blooming and vignetting, are also visible and occasionally distracting in darker HDR scenes. This causes bright objects to create a flashlight effect around darker backgrounds. Artifacts like this are common on local dimming TVs but appear a bit worse here than on competing models I\'ve tested. Blooming is less distracting on the NanoCell 90 than it has been on previous LG TVs, however, so the company has made some improvements in this regard.&nbsp;</p><h3><strong>Dolby Vision&nbsp;</strong></h3><p>It\'s also worth noting that I encountered some odd discrepancies when viewing <a href=\"https://www.businessinsider.com/what-is-hdr-tv\">Dolby Vision</a> content through different sources. When watching various Dolby Vision titles using the Cinema setting through the TV\'s built-in apps, like <a href=\"https://www.businessinsider.com/how-to-use-netflix-tips-and-tricks\">Netflix</a>, the picture appears unusually dim, often lacking the punch in highlights that one would expect from HDR content. On the plus side, local dimming artifacts are very minimal as a result.</p><p>When watching the same Dolby Vision titles using a Fire TV Stick 4K or Xbox One X connected to one of the TV\'s HDMI ports, however, highlights look brighter and more intense. At the same time, blooming from the local dimming is a lot more noticeable. This is also the case when watching the same streaming titles in HDR10 through a Roku Ultra connected to the TV.&nbsp;</p><p>I reached out to LG to see if there was a reason why this discrepancy was occurring. After looking into the matter, LG explains, \"The image quality processing of Dolby Vision content is the same on either internal app or HDMI input and has been verified during the Dolby Certification process. However, there might be additional enhancements from individual device manufacturers that could make the color and brightness appear different depending on the devices.\"</p><p>All things considered, I ultimately prefer to watch Dolby Vision content using my Fire TV Stick 4K since it seems to take better advantage of the TV\'s brightness capabilities and&nbsp; match the TV\'s HDR10 performance better.</p><h2 style=\"text-align:center;\"><strong>Smart TV features</strong></h2><figure class=\"image image_resized\" style=\"width:646.391px;\"><img src=\"https://i.insider.com/5f6e5e3e74fe5b0018a8d9eb?width=1300&amp;format=jpeg&amp;auto=webp\" alt=\"LG NanoCell 90 4K TV lifestyle in living room\"></figure><p>The <a href=\"https://www.businessinsider.com/reviews/out?platform=browser&amp;postSource=bi%7C61b8efc8f2a36b1ac9f42fb4&amp;sc=false&amp;sessionid=1641822206190y7l570qr&amp;type=ALREADY-AFFILIATE-LINK-NOT-AMAZON&amp;u=https%3A%2F%2Fbestbuy.7tiv.net%2Fc%2F196318%2F614286%2F10014%3Fu%3Dhttps%253A%252F%252Fwww.bestbuy.com%252Fsite%252Flg-65-class-nanocell-90-series-led-4k-uhd-smart-webos-tv%252F6401917.p%253FskuId%253D6401917%26subId3%3Dxid%3Afr1641822212082bga&amp;xid=fr1641822212082bga\">NanoCell 90</a> makes use of LG\'s webOS smart TV platform, offering a fast and responsive system with a nice assortment of apps and lifestyle features. The included Magic Remote provides built-in support for Google Assistant or Alexa, allowing buyers to choose which voice assistant they want to use. In practice, the digital assistant functionality and voice recognition work well, allowing you to easily search for content, launch apps, and find answers to various questions.&nbsp;</p><p><a href=\"https://www.businessinsider.com/how-to-watch-netflix-free-shows-movies\">Netflix</a>, <a href=\"https://www.businessinsider.com/disney-plus-review\">Disney Plus</a>, <a href=\"https://www.businessinsider.com/how-much-is-hulu\">Hulu</a>, <a href=\"https://www.businessinsider.com/how-to-use-prime-video\">Amazon Prime Video</a>, <a href=\"https://www.businessinsider.com/how-to-rent-movies-online#vudu-2\">Vudu</a>, <a href=\"https://www.businessinsider.com/apple-one-subscription-bundle-price-release-date#apple-tv-3\">Apple TV Plus</a>, <a href=\"https://www.businessinsider.com/peacock-streaming-service\">Peacock</a>, and virtually any other major streaming app you\'d want are also included. HDR10, Dolby Vision, and Dolby Atmos support are also supported when available. Unfortunately, there is one notable app omission that could be an issue for some customers: <a href=\"https://www.businessinsider.com/hbo-max-streaming-service\">HBO Max</a> is nowhere to be found. This service is also currently missing from Roku and Fire TV devices, so its exclusion here is especially disappointing.</p><p>Thankfully, general navigation is snappy and I haven\'t encountered any major issues with lag or crashes. Unlike some other streaming platforms, like <a href=\"https://www.businessinsider.com/what-is-android-tv\">Android TV</a> and the Roku OS, LG\'s webOS forgoes a typical fullscreen app homepage. Instead, pressing the home button on the remote pulls up a horizontal pop-up menu on the bottom of the screen with access to apps. Generally, this approach works just fine, and allows you to transition from one app to another without having to go back to a homepage.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>LG also includes access to LG Channels, which features a large assortment of free internet TV stations that can be integrated alongside over-the-air networks if you have an antenna. LG\'s free channel selection is powered by Xumo and includes stations like Cheddar News, American Classics, The Broadway Channel, and more. Free integrated channel lineups like this have become common on many smart TV platforms, but while a nice inclusion, they really don\'t serve as much of a substitute for cable or a full-fledged live TV service. In other words, I\'ve rarely found myself ever channel surfing this selection.&nbsp;</p><h2 style=\"text-align:center;\"><strong>The bottom line</strong></h2><figure class=\"image image_resized\" style=\"width:646.391px;\"><img src=\"https://i.insider.com/5f6e618f74fe5b0018a8da00?width=1300&amp;format=jpeg&amp;auto=webp\" alt=\"LG NanoCell 90 4K TV on wall\"></figure><p>LG\'s new <a href=\"https://www.businessinsider.com/reviews/out?platform=browser&amp;postSource=bi%7C61b8efc8f2a36b1ac9f42fb4&amp;sc=false&amp;sessionid=1641822206190a8dw2a3e&amp;type=ALREADY-AFFILIATE-LINK-NOT-AMAZON&amp;u=https%3A%2F%2Fbestbuy.7tiv.net%2Fc%2F196318%2F614286%2F10014%3Fu%3Dhttps%253A%252F%252Fwww.bestbuy.com%252Fsite%252Flg-65-class-nanocell-90-series-led-4k-uhd-smart-webos-tv%252F6401917.p%253FskuId%253D6401917%26subId3%3Dxid%3Afr1641822212083dbg&amp;xid=fr1641822212083dbg\">NanoCell 90 TV</a> offers solid overall performance, especially when it comes to smart features and viewing angles. On the downside, the display\'s brightness and contrast capabilities aren\'t on par with some cheaper TVs from brands like Vizio, TCL, and Hisense.</p><h3><strong>Should you buy it?</strong></h3><p>At $1,199.99, the <a href=\"https://www.businessinsider.com/reviews/out?platform=browser&amp;postSource=bi%7C61b8efc8f2a36b1ac9f42fb4&amp;sc=false&amp;sessionid=1641822206190sir9vt5e&amp;type=ALREADY-AFFILIATE-LINK-NOT-AMAZON&amp;u=https%3A%2F%2Fbestbuy.7tiv.net%2Fc%2F196318%2F614286%2F10014%3Fu%3Dhttps%253A%252F%252Fwww.bestbuy.com%252Fsite%252Flg-65-class-nanocell-90-series-led-4k-uhd-smart-webos-tv%252F6401917.p%253FskuId%253D6401917%26subId3%3Dxid%3Afr1641822212083eig&amp;xid=fr1641822212083eig\">65-inch NanoCell 90</a> is a decent buy for customers who want an LCD TV with wide viewing angles and comprehensive digital assistant support for their living room. Buyers who place more importance on high-end HDR performance, however, can find less expensive TVs that are better for that purpose.</p><p>If you\'d like a larger screen, the NanoCell 90 also comes in <a href=\"https://www.businessinsider.com/reviews/out?platform=browser&amp;postSource=bi%7C61b8efc8f2a36b1ac9f42fb4&amp;sc=false&amp;sessionid=1641822206190aefyg9rp&amp;type=ALREADY-AFFILIATE-LINK-NOT-AMAZON&amp;u=https%3A%2F%2Fbestbuy.7tiv.net%2Fc%2F196318%2F614286%2F10014%3Fu%3Dhttps%253A%252F%252Fwww.bestbuy.com%252Fsite%252Flg-75-class-nanocell-90-series-led-4k-uhd-smart-webos-tv%252F6401918.p%253FskuId%253D6401918%26subId3%3Dxid%3Afr1641822212083cbj&amp;xid=fr1641822212083cbj\">75-inch</a> ($1,999.99) and <a href=\"https://www.businessinsider.com/reviews/out?platform=browser&amp;postSource=bi%7C61b8efc8f2a36b1ac9f42fb4&amp;sc=false&amp;sessionid=1641822206190a7dxuldc&amp;type=ALREADY-AFFILIATE-LINK-NOT-AMAZON&amp;u=https%3A%2F%2Fbestbuy.7tiv.net%2Fc%2F196318%2F614286%2F10014%3Fu%3Dhttps%253A%252F%252Fwww.bestbuy.com%252Fsite%252Flg-86-class-nanocell-90-series-led-4k-uhd-smart-webos-tv%252F6401853.p%253FskuId%253D6401853%26subId3%3Dxid%3Afr1641822212083dfe&amp;xid=fr1641822212083dfe\">86-inch models</a> ($2,799.99). A <a href=\"https://www.businessinsider.com/reviews/out?platform=browser&amp;postSource=bi%7C61b8efc8f2a36b1ac9f42fb4&amp;sc=false&amp;sessionid=1641822206190nm6ge9gf&amp;type=ALREADY-AFFILIATE-LINK-NOT-AMAZON&amp;u=https%3A%2F%2Fbestbuy.7tiv.net%2Fc%2F196318%2F614286%2F10014%3Fu%3Dhttps%253A%252F%252Fwww.bestbuy.com%252Fsite%252Flg-55-class-nanocell-90-series-led-4k-uhd-smart-webos-tv%252F6401915.p%253FskuId%253D6401915%26subId3%3Dxid%3Afr1641822212083eac&amp;xid=fr1641822212083eac\">55-inch version</a> ($949.99) is also available. Please be aware, however, that brightness and dimming performance will likely vary depending on the size of the TV.&nbsp;</p><h3><strong>What are your alternatives?</strong></h3><p>There are several worthy 65-inch alternatives to the NanoCell 90 in the $800 to $1,200 price range. The <a href=\"https://www.businessinsider.com/reviews/out?platform=browser&amp;postSource=bi%7C61b8efc8f2a36b1ac9f42fb4&amp;sc=false&amp;sessionid=1641822206190mhlu2k0f&amp;type=ALREADY-AFFILIATE-LINK-NOT-AMAZON&amp;u=https%3A%2F%2Fbestbuy.7tiv.net%2Fc%2F196318%2F614286%2F10014%3Fu%3Dhttps%253A%252F%252Fwww.bestbuy.com%252Fsite%252Fhisense-65-class-h9g-quantum-series-led-4k-uhd-smart-android-tv%252F6404014.p%253FskuId%253D6404014%26subId3%3Dxid%3Afr1641822212083ada&amp;xid=fr1641822212083ada\">Hisense H9G</a> ($999.99), <a href=\"https://www.businessinsider.com/reviews/out?platform=browser&amp;postSource=bi%7C61b8efc8f2a36b1ac9f42fb4&amp;sc=false&amp;sessionid=1641822206191atuqyb6n&amp;type=ALREADY-AFFILIATE-LINK-NOT-AMAZON&amp;u=https%3A%2F%2Fbestbuy.7tiv.net%2Fc%2F196318%2F614286%2F10014%3Fu%3Dhttps%253A%252F%252Fwww.bestbuy.com%252Fsite%252Ftcl-65-class-6-series-led-4k-uhd-smart-roku-tv%252F6424216.p%253FskuId%253D6424216%26subId3%3Dxid%3Afr1641822212083bed&amp;xid=fr1641822212083bed\">TCL 6 Series</a> ($899.99), and <a href=\"https://www.businessinsider.com/reviews/out?platform=browser&amp;postSource=bi%7C61b8efc8f2a36b1ac9f42fb4&amp;sc=false&amp;sessionid=1641822206191ngadv6i8&amp;type=ALREADY-AFFILIATE-LINK-NOT-AMAZON&amp;u=https%3A%2F%2Fbestbuy.7tiv.net%2Fc%2F196318%2F614286%2F10014%3Fu%3Dhttps%253A%252F%252Fwww.bestbuy.com%252Fsite%252F65-class-p-series-quantum-series-led-4k-uhd-smart-vizio-smartcast-tv%252F6416449.p%253FskuId%253D6416449%26subId3%3Dxid%3Afr1641822212083bef&amp;xid=fr1641822212083bef\">Vizio P-Series Quantum</a> ($1,199.99), all feature brighter HDR capabilities and more local dimming zones, which should translate to a punchier image with deeper black levels. The Hisense and Vizio also add HDR10+ support, which is missing from the LG NanoCell 90.</p><p>On the downside, those competing models have worse viewing angles, are typically prone to more uniformity issues, and feature fewer built-in digital assistant options. The Hisense has a Google Assistant remote but lacks an integrated Alexa option. Meanwhile, the TCL uses Roku\'s voice search, and the Vizio lacks a voice remote entirely.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Pros:</strong> IPS screen with wide viewing angles, Magic Remote with integrated Google Assistant or Alexa, responsive smart TV platform, HDMI 2.1 ports</p><p><strong>Cons:</strong> Noticeable blooming in dark scenes when watching HDR content, peak brightness isn\'t as high as competing TVs, inconsistencies with Dolby Vision playback (possibly an external source or DV issue rather than the TV itself)</p>', 5),
